<title>Reading Rhythm 6: Using Different Notes for the Beat</title>
<metadata xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml">
  <md:content-id>m63105</md:content-id>
  <md:title>Reading Rhythm 6: Using Different Notes for the Beat</md:title>
  <md:abstract>When the time signature indicates the meter of a piece of music, that includes defining which type of note lasts for one beat. Although the most common meters use the quarter note, any note can be defined as being the note that is one beat long. Half-note beats and eighth-note beats are both fairly common.</md:abstract>
  <md:uuid>cd8c4607-e813-4e7f-b5e1-29a8631bc3c3</md:uuid>
</metadata>

<content>
  <note id="eip-648">This lesson is part of <link document="col12057">Reading Rhythm</link>, a <link document="m62540">learning by doing</link> course intended to help you learn and practice the rhythm aspect of common notation. The pitch aspect of common notation is not covered in this course, so it can be used with any instrument, including voice, or with no instrument at all (using, for example, hand claps instead). This is a short experimental course that will be refined and expanded if there is sufficient user interest and feedback.</note><para id="eip-200">As discussed in <link document="m62591">Lesson 1</link>, any type of note can last for one beat. Up to this point, all of the activities in these lessons have used meters in which a quarter note is the "one beat long" note. These meters include 4/4, 3/4/, and 2/4, which together account for a very large proportion of music written in common notation. However, meters in which either a half note or an eighth note is the "one beat long" note are also reasonably common. <emphasis>The bottom number in the time signature indicates which type of note gets one beat</emphasis>. (The top note still indicates the number of beats in the measure, as in earlier lessons.) This lesson provides practice with these types of meters and also demonstrates how you can use them to figure out and practice rhythms that are unfamiliar or challenging.</para><section id="eip-76"><title>Meters that use half-note or eighth-note beats</title>

<figure id="half-note-beat-figure"><media id="half-note-beat" alt="Three staves, indicating that 2/2 time is equivalent to 4/4 and 8/8 time">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/half-note-beat.png"/>
  </media>
  
<caption>The bottom number in the time signature indicates what type of note lasts for one beat. The same piece can be written with an eighth note getting one beat, or a quarter note, or a half note. If these are played at the same tempo (same number of beats per minute), then 4/4 time would be twice as fast as 2/2 time. But if the tempo of the 4/4 time is twice as fast (twice as many beats per minute) as the 2/2 time, then they would sound exactly the same. (For examples, see the audio files associated with <link target-id="activity7-1-figure"/> below.)
  </caption></figure><para id="eip-513">Which time signature to use is a decision made by the person who writes the music (the composer, arranger, or transcriber). The decision is usually made based on genre traditions, as well as on what the writer believes is most intuitive, easiest to read, and most suggestive of the underlying pulse of the music. For the person reading the music, the most important thing to understand is that the decision does not affect the sound of the music. <emphasis>It is the <link document="m62591" target-id="eip-260">tempo</link> that actually determines the speed of the piece, not the type of note that is given one beat.</emphasis> Tempo can be suggested by the writer, but the performer actually decides the tempo. A piece can be written with an eighth note getting one beat, or a quarter note, or a half note. A measure of 2/2 can have the same rhythms as a measure of 4/4 or a measure of 8/8, and the meters of these time signatures are so similar that they can be impossible to distinguish by ear.</para><list id="eip-404" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic"><title>Activity 1: Practice reading with half-note beats</title><item>Using any favorite <link document="m62591" target-id="eip-405">method of keeping a steady beat</link> and <link document="m62591" target-id="eip-494">method of practicing rhythms</link>, try to read and play the examples in <link target-id="activity7-1-figure"/>.</item>
<item>If you are having trouble reading the lines as written, imagine that they are written in the equivalent quarter-note-beat meter. (For example, imagine that 2/2 is written as 4/4 and 3/2 is written as 6/4). When you can play a line in a fast quarter-note-beat meter, play the line again at exactly the same speed, but with the beat at half the speed.</item>
<item>Practice each example more than once using the indicated meter, then listen to the sound files to check whether you have played them correctly.</item>
<item>If needed, try playing along with the sound files.</item></list><figure id="activity7-1-figure"><title>Practice Examples: Half-Note Beats</title><media id="activity7-1" alt="Three lines of mixed whole, half, and quarter notes and rests: two in 2/2 time and one in 3/2 time.">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/activity7-1.png"/>
  </media>
</figure>

