<list id="eip-396" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic"><title>Activity 2: Practice reading with eighth-note beats</title><item>Using any favorite method of keeping the beat and practicing rhythms, try to read and play the examples in <link target-id="activity7-2-figure"/>.</item>
<item>If you are having trouble reading the lines as written, imagine that they are written in the equivalent quarter-note-beat meter. For example, imagine that 4/8 is written as 2/4 and 2/8 is written as 1/4 (an unusual meter, but technically allowed). When you can play a line in a slow quarter-note-beat meter, play the line again at exactly the same speed, but with the beat at twice the speed.</item>
<item>Practice each example more than once using the indicated meter, then listen to the sound files to check whether you have played them correctly.</item>
<item>If needed, try playing along with the sound files.</item></list><figure id="activity7-2-figure"><title>Practice Examples: Eighth-Note Beats</title><media id="activity7-2" alt="Three lines of mixed half and quarter notes and rests, and eighth notes: two in 4/8 time, and one in 2/8 time.">
