<list id="eip-362" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic"><title>Activity 3: Practice writing eighth-note or half-note beats</title><item>Use your preferred <link document="m62677" target-id="eip-782">methods of writing down music</link>, setting up a steady beat, and playing what you have written.</item>
<item>Try writing down your own lines with either eighth-note or half-note time signatures. You may find that you can use lines that you have written for previous lessons and simply change the time signature.</item>
<item>Try playing what you have written. Feel free to make changes as needed to create rhythms that you like and that you believe fit nicely into the time signature you have used.</item>
<item>As you did with the <link document="m62677" target-id="eip-782">writing activity in Lesson 2</link>, practice and check until you are certain that you are playing your written rhythms correctly.</item></list>

<para id="eip-613">The 2/2 time signature is probably the most common meter that does not use a quarter-note beat. Like <term>common time</term> (4/4) time], it has a short-cut symbol that represents it, which is called <term>cut time</term> (2/2 time) and looks like a common-time marking "cut" in half with a vertical line.</para><figure id="common-cut-figure"><media id="common-and-cut" alt="Four staves with time signatures, indicating that a C in the time signature position is equivalent to 4/4 time and a C with a vertical line through it in the time signature position is equivalent to 2/2 time.">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/common-and-cut.png"/>
  </media>
</figure>

</section>
<section id="eip-77"><title>Changing the beat in order to read and practice difficult rhythms</title>

<para id="eip-249">One instance when it can be useful to give an eighth note the beat is when the music includes notes that are even shorter than eighth notes. By adding more flags or beams, you can continue to divide note lengths in half to get ever shorter notes. Half of an eighth note is a <term>sixteenth note</term>, half of a sixteenth note is a <term>thirty-second note</term>, and so on. (Thirty-second notes are rare, and anything shorter very rare.) </para>

<figure id="sixteenth-notes-figure">
  <media id="sixteenth-notes" alt="Sixteenth notes, stem up and down, with flags and with beams, and thirty-second and sixty-fourth notes with beams">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/sixteenth-notes.png"/>
  </media>
</figure>

<para id="eip-49">When a quarter note gets one beat, there are four sixteenth notes (or eight thirty-second notes) in one beat, which can be quite challenging to play correctly (see the examples in <link target-id="eights-sixteenths-figure"/>). You may already have come across other rhythms in these lessons (or in real music) that you have found difficult to play correctly, or even difficult to decide how they are supposed to sound. If it has not happened yet, it is likely to happen at some point as you read increasingly challenging music. When it happen, you may find it useful to slow the music down, to give you time to think about or to play the rhythm correctly. However, very slow beats are difficult to keep steady, so rather than keep a very slow quarter-note beat (for example), it can be very useful to “pretend” that the meter is has an eighth-note beat, for practice purposes (see <link target-id="activity7-3-figure"/>). In music, just as in mathematics, 2/2 and 4/4 and 8/8 are all completely equivalent; they are only written differently because in some circumstances it is more useful to divide the whole into eighths rather than into quarters or halves.</para>

<figure id="eights-sixteenths-figure"><title>Reading Complex Rhythms</title><media id="eights-sixteenths" alt="Eighth notes and sixteenth notes beamed together to equal one quarter note">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/eights-sixteenths.png"/>
  </media>
  
<caption>One way that the person writing the music helps readers is by grouping notes by beat (most commonly the quarter-note beat). When a single beat contains a mixture of notes, they are typically beamed together so that the reader can see at a glance that they must all be played in the course of a single beat. When this is the case, play each note according to the highest number of beams touching the stem.
  </caption></figure>

<list id="eip-761" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic"><title>Activity 4: Use eighth-note beats to practice playing sixteenth notes</title><item>Choose a favorite, easy method of making sounds.</item>
<item>Use a favorite method to set up a relatively fast-paced steady beat. This will be your eighth-note-gets-one-beat tempo.</item>
<item>First practice the examples in <link target-id="activity7-3-figure"/> that use eighth note beats (examples A, C, and E). Notice that when an eighth note gets a beat, there are only two sixteenth notes in a beat. In other words, in eighth-note-beat meters, sixteenth notes will feel just like eighth notes in quarter-note-beat time signatures, which should make them feel familiar and easy to play correctly.
</item>
<item>Check the audio files to make sure you are playing them correctly.</item>
<item>Once you are playing a line correctly in the eighth-note-beat meter, switch to playing the version of the same line that is written in the quarter-note-beat time signature. Notice that sixteenth notes now must be played four-to-a-beat. At first, practice with the beat at half speed, so that it sounds exactly the same as the eighth-note-beat version.
</item>
<item>If possible, speed up the quarter-note tempo so that you are playing the sixteenth notes very quickly. Challenge yourself to see how quickly you can play them accurately and evenly. Can you speed up the tempo even more by switching to a different method of “playing” (for example, singing syllables, or tapping on a table with alternating hands, rather than clapping hands)?</item></list>

<figure id="activity7-3-figure"><title>Practice Examples: Switching Beats</title><media id="activity7-3" alt="Description...">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/activity7-3.png"/>
  </media>
<caption>Every flag or beam that is added to the stem of a note cuts its time length in half again. For example, notes with two flags or beams are sixteenth notes, which last half as long as eighth notes. Notes with three flags or beams are thirty-second notes, which last half as long as sixteenth notes.</caption></figure>

