<list id="eip-377"><title>Suggestions for practice with "real music":</title><item>When you listen to favorite pieces of music, listen for very fast notes in the rhythm. Notice that this means you are listening for notes that are very quickly followed by other notes. This is not the same as notes that are short simply for the effect, with plenty of time after them in the rhythm. Are any note rhythms quick enough that at least four of them could fit in one beat? Which instruments play the quick rhythms?</item>
<item>If you have any written music for your instrument that includes sixteenth notes, see whether you can play it by reading the music. 
</item>
<item>For now, continue to avoid music in which the rhythms use dots, but if you have come across other rhythms that you find challenging, try using a slower meter to figure them out and practice them.</item>
<item>If you have any music written with a half-note-beat meter, including "cut time," or with an eighth-note-beat meter, try playing it. (Note that 3/8 and 6/8 music does not translate well to any quarter-note-beat meter, so practice these meters ONLY with an eighth-note beat. This will be discussed in the next lesson.)</item>
<item>If you are singing in a choir with a conductor and with written music, start noticing any sixteenth notes in the music. Also notice any examples of pieces that use a note other than the quarter note for a beat. What tempo does the conductor choose for these pieces, and how does the meter seem to affect the conducting pattern?</item></list>


</section>

